{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d2ca6cb8-77f6-46a9-8f25-42bd8933f965","content":"The directory is empty — there's no project yet. But I can give you exactly what you need to configure. Here's the key setup for publishing a .NET tool to NuGet:\n\n### In your `.csproj`, add these properties:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- Required for dotnet tool packaging -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</RepositoryUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key properties explained:\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Makes `dotnet pack` produce a tool package |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users type (e.g., `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `PackageId` | The NuGet package name |\n\n### Publish steps:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server              # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the core of it — `PackAsTool` + `ToolCommandName` are the two critical properties that turn a console app into an installable dotnet tool.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b1b2f9dc-937f-4a22-bf72-127b09f07c00","outputTokens":540},"id":"2bbe88bd-077c-4e0d-95b7-bde57f619558","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:48:56.483Z","parentId":"3fcc595a-c399-4c0a-8002-e0a8e3424bdc"}
